{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480898"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:53:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:53:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"123"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/123"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.24,0.07,0.01,0.64]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77131"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/123"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62637"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3233"},{"type":"tags","id":"3340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6217"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6332"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41996"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77131"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department by her son following an unconscious collapse at home. She has a medical history of schizophrenia and bipolar disorder. Her regular medications include risperidone which she has taken for many years, and lithium which was started two weeks ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has been unwell for several days with fever, rigors and confusion. On examination, she appears unwell. Her vital signs have been fluctuating with blood pressure ranging from 90/50 to 150/70 mmHg, pulse rate 110/min, respiratory rate 22/min, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. She is not rousable to voice. There is generalised rigidity in all four limbs with normal reflexes and downgoing plantar responses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malignant hyperthermia","Lithium toxicity","Serotonin syndrome","Drug hypersensitivity","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Eneuroleptic malignant syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (NMS): fever, altered consciousness, muscle rigidity, and autonomic instability. The gradual onset over days and recent addition of lithium to long-term risperidone therapy are typical precipitants. Laboratory testing would typically show elevated creatine kinase levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerotonin syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically develops more rapidly (within 24 hours) and features hyperreflexia and clonus rather than \u0027lead-pipe\u0027 rigidity. It occurs with serotonergic medications, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELithium toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with gastrointestinal symptoms, tremor, and confusion. While this patient recently started lithium, the muscle rigidity and fever are more consistent with NMS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant hyperthermia\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare genetic disorder triggered by certain anaesthetic agents, presenting with rapid onset hyperthermia, muscle rigidity, and metabolic acidosis. There is no history of anaesthetic exposure here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug hypersensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E reactions typically feature cutaneous manifestations such as rash, which are absent in this case. While fever and autonomic instability can occur, the prominent muscle rigidity points towards NMS.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neuroleptic malignant syndrome presents with fever, \u0027lead-pipe\u0027 muscle rigidity, altered consciousness, autonomic dysfunction, and elevated creatine kinase.","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome typically develops over days rather than hours, distinguishing it from serotonin syndrome which develops more rapidly.","Recent changes in antipsychotic medications or addition of lithium can trigger Neuroleptic malignant syndrome."],"references":["Tse L, Barr AM. Scarapicchia V, et al. Neuroleptic Malignant Syndrome: A Review from a Clinically Oriented Perspective. Curr Neuropharm. 2015;13:395-406. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26411967/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62637"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"123"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62637"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T09:41:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T09:41:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"123"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77131"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":